rigin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Sir Robert Cromwelbotham was born about 1295, in Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Mrs Robert Cromwelbotham. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1295–":"umbes 1295–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1310–Male":"1310–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","about 1295":"umbes 1295","Cromwell Bottom Hall, Southowram, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southowram, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cromwelbotham, Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",ENGLAND":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cromwelbotham Hall, Southowram, Halifax Parish, West Riding, Yorkshire, England":"St Ann in the Grove's Church, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1295–":"noin 1295–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1310–Male":"1310–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1295–Male":"1295–Kuollut","1310":"1310","1320":"1320","1295":"1295","about 1295":"noin 1295","Cromwell Bottom Hall, Southowram, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Southowram, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cromwelbotham, Yorkshire